channel.description:
The Goal:
- Create both a jar and URL loader.

Requirements:
- Moderate java knowledge
- An IDE of your choice
- Some very basic web programming knowledge

Notes:
- I will be including snippets from the JavaDocs throughout the tutorial, but I highly recommend you explore further.  The official JavaDocs can be found at http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/

The Tutorial:

This tutorial will focus on the main base for your bot.  The loader.  The loader is what "loads" the runescape applet into the GUI of your bot.  Without using a loader, you would be forced to use the applet right off the runescape site, which would prevent minimization.  A good example of this kind of bot is SCAR.

The loader is a very useful tool, but it should be done correctly.  A "dirty" loader could easily result in a ban.

There are two types of loaders, a URL loader (a URLClassLoader) and a jar loader (a JarClassLoader).  The URL loader loads all the data and the applet right off the runescape site.  The jar loader loads runescape from a jar file on the local filesystem (this method is used for all bytecode bots).

[size=20pt][b]URL Class Loader: [/b][/size]

Okay.  So, let's go over exactly what it is we will need to do.  First, we need to make a basic GUI to hold our applet.  Next, we will need to parse all the "applet parameters" to our applet, and set the stub for our parameters.  We can the launch the applet.

This might sound easy, and it truly is, but it can take some time depending on how efficent you are.

We will be using Swing for this tutorial.  Why?  SWT sucks balls.  End of story.

Now, moving right along.

We need to create a class, and have it extend a Swing frame.  Here is our base (Note: I called my class RSLoader).

[code]public class RSLoader extends javax.swing.JFrame implements java.applet.AppletStub {

	public RSLoader() {

	}

}[/code]

Before we continue, let's consider something together.  In order to load the applet, we have to pass it arguments.  In other words, we need to setup the "stub" of the applet.  The arguments themselves are mostly rudimentary things, like if the game is english.

We will come back to this later.  For now, let's just continue.

We need to create a new frame.

[code]setResizable(false);
			setTitle("Runescape Loader");
			setVisible(true);[/code]

Now an empty loader will appear.  Before we can start the loader, we need to set the stub with the parameters we need.  There are two ways to go about doing this.  We can hardcode each parameter into the loader, or we can parse the parameters off of the runescape website.

Obviously, hard coding them is much easier, but parsing them is much safer.

However, since hardcoding them is still acceptable (seeing as RSBot uses hardcoded parameters), I will start with doing it this way, then show you how to parse them later.

First, we need to create a new HashMap to hold our values.

[code]private static final HashMap<String, String> parameters = new HashMap<String, String>();[/code]

For your ease of use, and my time, I have copied a small excerpt from the JavaDocs regarding the HashMap class.  I do highly suggest you look into the Javadocs yourself and explore further, I am simply placing this here for simplicity.  The java 6 docs can be found at http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/ .

<blockquote>Hash table based implementation of the Map interface. This implementation provides all of the optional map operations, and permits null values and the null key. (The HashMap  class is roughly equivalent to Hashtable, except that it is unsynchronized and permits nulls.) This class makes no guarantees as to the order of the map; in particular, it does not guarantee that the order will remain constant over time.

This implementation provides constant-time performance for the basic operations (get and put), assuming the hash function disperses the elements properly among the buckets. Iteration over collection views requires time proportional to the "capacity" of the HashMap instance (the number of buckets) plus its size (the number of key-value mappings). Thus, it's very important not to set the initial capacity too high (or the load factor too low) if iteration performance is important.

An instance of HashMap has two parameters that affect its performance: initial capacity and load factor. The capacity is the number of buckets in the hash table, and the initial capacity is simply the capacity at the time the hash table is created. The load factor is a measure of how full the hash table is allowed to get before its capacity is automatically increased. When the number of entries in the hash table exceeds the product of the load factor and the current capacity, the hash table is rehashed (that is, internal data structures are rebuilt) so that the hash table has approximately twice the number of buckets.</blockquote>

So, basically, we are using the hashmap to store our values.

These are really the only parameters we need to start the loader:

[code]parameters.put("height", "762");
			parameters.put("width", "503");
			parameters.put("worldid", "37");
			parameters.put("members", "0");
			parameters.put("modewhat", "0");
			parameters.put("modewhere", "0");
			parameters.put("safemode", "1");
			parameters.put("lang", "0");[/code]

Please make note of the "worldid" parameter.  We replace that with whatever world you want to load.  So, in your loader, you may want to replace it with a variable holding the user selected world number.

[i]NOTE: This will probably eventually get you banned.  I HIGHLY suggest parsing the parameters instead.  But, since both methods are in use today, I will explain both.[/i]

Next, we create a new instance of the "client" class.  For those who don't know much about client hacking, the "client" class is the main class in the client.  It is what loads the game etc.

So, our goal is to make a new instance of the client class.  For this, we need to load the client class.  For that, we use a client class loader :D.

[code]clientClassLoader = new URLClassLoader(new URL[] { new URL(
					"http://world37.runescape.com/runescape.jar") });[/code]

Once again, take note of "world37".  In your bot, you may want to replace this with a user selected variable.

Basically, this creates a new URLClassLoader which we use to load classes from the runescape JAR, without having it on our current filesystem.

Here is another excerpt from the javadocs regarding the URLClassLoader:

<blockquote>This class loader is used to load classes and resources from a search path of URLs referring to both JAR files and directories. Any URL that ends with a '/' is assumed to refer to a directory. Otherwise, the URL is assumed to refer to a JAR file which will be opened as needed.

The AccessControlContext of the thread that created the instance of URLClassLoader will be used when subsequently loading classes and resources.

The classes that are loaded are by default granted permission only to access the URLs specified when the URLClassLoader was created.</blockquote>

Our next step is to setup the "stub" of the applet.  A stub is a routine that doesn't actually do anything other than declare itself and the parameters it accepts. Stubs are used commonly as placeholders for routines that still need to be developed. The stub contains just enough code to allow it to be compiled and linked with the rest of the program.

Setting the stub for our loader couldn't be easier.  Since we are already implementing AppletStub, we just go:

[code]loader.setStub(this);[/code]

Now, before we continue, let's take a look at what we have so far:

[code]
import java.applet.Applet;
import java.applet.AppletContext;
import java.net.URL;
import java.net.URLClassLoader;
import java.util.HashMap;

public class RSLoader extends javax.swing.JFrame implements
		java.applet.AppletStub {
	private static final HashMap<String, String> parameters = new HashMap<String, String>();

	public RSLoader() {
		try {
			setResizable(false);
			setTitle("Runescape Loader ~ The Bank");
			setVisible(true);
			parameters.put("height", "762");
			parameters.put("width", "503");
			parameters.put("worldid", "37");
			parameters.put("members", "0");
			parameters.put("modewhat", "0");
			parameters.put("modewhere", "0");
			parameters.put("safemode", "1");
			parameters.put("lang", "0");
			ClassLoader clientClassLoader = new URLClassLoader(
					new URL[] { new URL(
							"http://world37.runescape.com/runescape.jar") });
			Class<?> clientClass = clientClassLoader.loadClass("client");
			Applet loader = (Applet) clientClass.newInstance();
			loader.setStub(this);
		} catch (Exception e) {
			e.printStackTrace();
		}
	}

	public void appletResize(int width, int height) {

	}

	public final URL getCodeBase() {
		try {
			return new URL("http://world37.runescape.com/");
		} catch (Exception e) {
			return null;
		}
	}

	public final URL getDocumentBase() {
		try {
			return new URL("http://world37.runescape.com/");
		} catch (Exception e) {
			return null;
		}
	}

	public final String getParameter(String name) {
		return parameters.get(name);
	}

	public final AppletContext getAppletContext() {
		return null;
	}
}
[/code]

[i]NOTE: Note the five methods at the bottom.  They are auto generated when you implement AppletStub.[/i]

Now that we have everything in place, we can go ahead and start the applet!  After which, we should set the size of the applet and the JPanel which will be holding the applet.  To do this is very simple.

[code]loader.init();
			loader.start();

			JPopupMenu.setDefaultLightWeightPopupEnabled(false);
			JPanel theGame = new JPanel(new BorderLayout());
			theGame.setPreferredSize(new Dimension(768, 560));
			setPreferredSize(new Dimension(768, 658));
			theGame.add(loader);
			getContentPane().add(loader, BorderLayout.CENTER);
			setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
			setSize(769, 531);[/code]

First, we start the initiate the applet, then we start it.  We disable LightWeightPopups for the sake of detectability.  Next, we create a new JPanel which will hold our applet.  We set the prefered size (I got those dimensions via trial and error and found them to be the best.  Anyone know why?).  Then we add the applet to the JPanel.  Set it so that the entire application will shutdown when the frame is closed, and set the size.

If we bung all of this together we get:

[code]
import java.applet.Applet;
import java.applet.AppletContext;
import java.awt.BorderLayout;
import java.awt.Dimension;
import java.net.URL;
import java.net.URLClassLoader;
import java.util.HashMap;

import javax.swing.JPanel;
import javax.swing.JPopupMenu;

public class RSLoader extends javax.swing.JFrame implements
		java.applet.AppletStub {
	private static final HashMap<String, String> parameters = new HashMap<String, String>();

	public RSLoader() {
		try {
			setResizable(false);
			setTitle("Runescape Loader ~ The Bank");
			setVisible(true);
			parameters.put("height", "762");
			parameters.put("width", "503");
			parameters.put("worldid", "37");
			parameters.put("members", "0");
			parameters.put("modewhat", "0");
			parameters.put("modewhere", "0");
			parameters.put("safemode", "1");
			parameters.put("lang", "0");
			ClassLoader clientClassLoader = new URLClassLoader(
					new URL[] { new URL(
							"http://world37.runescape.com/runescape.jar") });
			Class<?> clientClass = clientClassLoader.loadClass("client");
			Applet loader = (Applet) clientClass.newInstance();
			loader.setStub(this);
			loader.init();
			loader.start();

			JPopupMenu.setDefaultLightWeightPopupEnabled(false);
			JPanel theGame = new JPanel(new BorderLayout());
			theGame.setPreferredSize(new Dimension(768, 560));
			setPreferredSize(new Dimension(768, 658));
			theGame.add(loader);
			getContentPane().add(loader, BorderLayout.CENTER);
			setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
			setSize(769, 531);
		} catch (Exception e) {
			e.printStackTrace();
		}
	}

	public void appletResize(int width, int height) {
		// TODO Auto-generated method stub

	}

	public final URL getCodeBase() {
		try {
			return new URL("http://world37.runescape.com/");
		} catch (Exception e) {
			return null;
		}
	}

	public final URL getDocumentBase() {
		try {
			return new URL("http://world37.runescape.com/");
		} catch (Exception e) {
			return null;
		}
	}

	public final String getParameter(String name) {
		return parameters.get(name);
	}

	public final AppletContext getAppletContext() {
		return null;
	}

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		new RSLoader().setVisible(true);
	}
}
[/code]

As you can see, I added the "main" method to the class.  In your bot, you would probably want to create a new loader in a separate class, but since we are just working with this one, we will make it here.

If you compile + run this, the applet will load up in our jpanel, and our loader is done!

So, now we understand that, let's try parsing the parameters from the web page!

Now, the parameters are not (unfortunately) viewable via View -> Page Source in your web browser.  So, instead we need to read the page via java.  In order to do this, we will use these functions.

[i]NOTE: One of the functions is simply a shortcut function for the other.  I do not take credit for this function.  All credit goes to the origional creator whom I do not know.  Maybe psb?[/i]

[code]private String readPage(URL url) throws IOException, InterruptedException {
		String s = readPage(url, referer);
		referer = url.toExternalForm();
		return s;
	}

	private String readPage(URL url, String referer) throws IOException,
			InterruptedException {
		URLConnection uc = url.openConnection();
		uc
				.addRequestProperty(
						"Accept",
						"text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5");
		uc.addRequestProperty("Accept-Charset",
				"ISO-8859-1,utf-8;q=0.7,*;q=0.7");
		uc.addRequestProperty("Accept-Encoding", "gzip,deflate");
		uc.addRequestProperty("Accept-Language", "en-gb,en;q=0.5");
		uc.addRequestProperty("Connection", "keep-alive");
		uc.addRequestProperty("Host", "www.runescape.com");
		uc.addRequestProperty("Keep-Alive", "300");
		if (referer != null)
			uc.addRequestProperty("Referer", referer);
		uc
				.addRequestProperty(
						"User-Agent",
						"Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-GB; rv:1.8.0.6) Gecko/20060728 Firefox/1.5.0.6");
		DataInputStream di = new DataInputStream(uc.getInputStream());
		byte[] buffer = new byte[uc.getContentLength()];
		di.readFully(buffer);
		di.close();
		Thread.sleep(250 + (int) Math.random() * 500);
		return new String(buffer);
	}[/code]

